	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Structural reorganisation and new strategy required for Caribbean cocoa sector</h1>

			
			<h4>
												20 August 2012
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>Addressing the 3<sup>rd</sup> Annual Caribbean Fine Cocoa Conference in June 2012, Jamaican Minister of Agriculture Roger Clarke called for an expansion of cocoa production and the initiation of ‘value-added activity in order to take advantage of the premium price paid for the commodity on the world market’. To date, little value addition takes place in the Caribbean’s eight countries that produce fine cocoa. Mr Clarke maintained that a structural reorganisation of the sector was required, with the government of Jamaica embarking on ‘a programme of divestment of its commercial interest in the sector’. This is seen as essential, in view of the decline in the sector in the last decade. This needs to be seen in the context of ministerial concerns that emerged in April over the financial consequences for cocoa farmers of the operation of the Jamaican Cocoa Industry Board. The Minister of Agriculture argued that ‘growth of the industry will have to be driven by expanded production through strategic alliances with those from the North to whom we sell our cocoa to undertake the value added in our territories.’</p><p>The Minister of Trade and Industry of Trinidad and Tobago, Vasant Bharath, took a more upbeat view, arguing that ‘after many years of declining production levels, the cocoa industry is undergoing a renaissance.’ Mr Bharath endorsed the view of Mr Clarke on the need to move up the value chain, observing that ‘cocoa is a multi-million industry but primary cocoa captures only a very small portion of the total value…The largest returns from this industry come from the value-added products such as chocolate and refined cocoa rather than cocoa beans, the primary commodity. It is therefore imperative that we promote greater investments in the value chain which is critical to the viability of the region’s cocoa industry.’</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>Jamaican Ministry of Agriculture, ‘Agriculture Minister Roger Clarke urges Caribbean nations to increase cocoa production and value-added activities’, 29 June 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://www.moa.gov.jm/News/2012/2012-06-29_Agriculture_Minister_Roger_Clarke_urges_Caribbean_nations_to_increase_cocoa_production_and_value_added_activity.php" target="_self">http://www.moa.gov.jm/News/2012/2012-06-29_Agriculture_Minister_Roger_Cl...</a></p><p><i>Jamaica Gleaner</i>, ‘This cannot continue – agriculture minister awaits audit findings on several agencies’, 12 May 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20120502/news/news3.html" target="_self">http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20120502/news/news3.html</a></p><p><i>Go-jamaica.com</i>, ‘Regional collaboration key to cocoa success’, 9 July 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://go-jamaica.com/pressrelease/item.php?id=758" target="_self">http://go-jamaica.com/pressrelease/item.php?id=758</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>A focus of discussion in the Caribbean Fine Cocoa Forum (CFCF – an-EU supported regional fine cocoa stakeholder dialogue forum) has been on getting cocoa estates back into production. The neglect and abandonment of cocoa estates in the Caribbean has been a key factor in the decline of both cocoa production and quality. Cocoa is now predominantly a smallholder farmer crop (e.g. 83% of Jamaica cocoa farmers operate on less than 5 hectares), with a number of current initiatives aimed at improving smallholder production of fine cocoa. This includes a 3-year programme funded by the ACP Centre for the Development of Excellence (CDE) launched in June 2011, and the EU-funded RECREATE programme in Jamaica launched in March 2012 (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Cocoa/Caribbean-looking-to-boost-cocoa-production" target="_blank">Caribbean looking to boost cocoa production</a>’, 10 June 2012).</p><p>The CDE project is tackling the issue of productivity and quality at source, with plans to use Farmer Field Schools to deliver training in good field and environmental practices, improved propagation capacity and post-harvest techniques, among other measures. This is supported by germplasm programmes implemented through the International Cocoa Gene Bank in Trinidad, which is seeking to extend use of improved varieties.</p><p>In terms of value-addition objectives, the CDE project involves a component targeting small-scale cocoa manufacturers and chocolate makers, providing training for advanced artisan chocolatiers and chefs in chocolate making and advanced chocolate product development techniques. Currently in the Caribbean there are only a limited number of small and medium enterprises&nbsp; involved in value-added cocoa products, ranging from cocoa drinks and chocolates to beauty and health care products, and even cocoa paper.</p><p>The CFCF has acknowledged that value addition must be central to cocoa industry restructuring and growth, moving beyond simply trading on the region’s reputation for fine or flavour cocoa. Increasingly issues related to certification, including respect for environmental and ethical standards along the cocoa value chain, will need to be addressed as an integral part of industry restructuring strategies.</p><p>Currently the challenges faced in moving the Caribbean cocoa industry higher up the value chain are twofold:</p>
<ul>

<li>production and processing-related issues (disease, certification, cost of labour, mechanisation of operations); </li>

<li>corporate issues related to the identification of strategic alliances with international chocolate companies capable of building up local value-added processing industries. </li>

</ul>
<p>Currently the production challenges in both the smallholder and estate sectors appear to be diverting attention away from the mobilisation of the investments required to build up a diversified Caribbean cocoa and chocolate products industry, with a focus falling on scaling up production of beans for export to established multinational partners.</p>
		</div>
		
